"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-nbc-peacock-gold-zone-has-perfected-live-olympics-coverage-paris\", \"text\": \"There\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s something different about these Olympics, and it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not just E. coli on the triathlon course or a beach volleyball stadium at the foot of the Eiffel Tower. As both a lifelong fan of the Olympics and a media membercovering the Gamesfrom the U.S., I can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t overstate how much my viewing experience has been enhanced by the emergence ofGold Zone, NBC\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099sNFL RedZone\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093style whip-around show taking us around Paris for 10 hours a day.  I also knowI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m not alone here. If NBC were to pull the plug on this product for future Olympics, some fans would be as angry as if the IOC yanked track and field.  I wrote a little aboutGold Zonebefore the Olympics, in the form ofa Q&A with Scott Hanson, one of the program\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s four daily hosts. I wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t planning on writing about it again, but then I consumed so much of the show that I felt like I couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t go 16 days without singing its praises.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIf at the end of the Games, people tell me,That felt like RedZone. Or,That gave me some RedZone\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093esque thrills, that will be mission accomplished,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Hanson told me in May. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIf casual Olympics fans tell me at the end of the Games that they watched more Olympics than they ever have because ofGold Zone, that will be mission accomplished.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Well,mission accomplished.  Gold Zoneis not actually new, but this is the Olympics in which NBC has perfected it. Thanks to better technology, a greater acceptance of watching live sports on streaming platforms and a better time zone, this has been the Olympics when the show broke through.  The program has done many things right, and those four hosts (Hanson, Andrew Siciliano, Matt Iseman and Jac Collinsworth) belong on that list. Each has brought their own cadence to the show, and the regular daily handoffs keep the proceedings from getting monotonous\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094especially for those of us who just keep the show running all day.  I figured who better to explain the success of the show than one of those hosts, so I connected with Iseman, who tag-teams the first time slot of the day with Collinsworth. What I got when Iseman picked up the phone was \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 both Iseman and Collinsworth on speakerphone. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s unclear when they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve last left each other\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s side.  The two hosts, who have spent the past 14 days encouraging fans to tweet photos of themselves watchingGold Zone, shared with me the routine of howtheywatchGold Zone. Their daily ritual: They get off set, grab a bite to eat and then sit on a balcony in their Stamford, Conn., hotel and watch Siciliano and Hanson.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cNot for research,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Iseman says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBut because we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re fans of this. Welovewatching it.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI think it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s probably the most fun [time] that I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve had on TV,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Collinsworth says. The pair were relatively fresh off the air and clearly still in a post-show buzz. They sounded just like they do on camera, jumping in to build off each other\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s points and bursting with nuggets to share.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve both been saying, you will never watch the Olympics the same way again,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Iseman adds.  I think he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s right.  What hooked me onGold Zonefrom the jump is that the show matches my sensibilities exactly. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve always thought outlets covering the Olympics could do a better job leaning into the more niche sports. People love it when a dressage horse or a badminton rally goes viral. But NBC\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s prime-time coverage still focuses so much on the biggest sports and most famous athletes, with maybe a few highlights from elsewhere.Gold Zone\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s multiscreen capabilities and longer runtime lend space to invest a bit of time just to see what might happen\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094as well as the good sense to know you can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t pull away when a wild ending in a France vs. Germany handball game falls in your lap. The show\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s real secret sauce is how it figured out that mix.  Gold Zoneprides itself on showing you every medal. This was made clear during \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cGold Rush Weekend,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Days 8 and 9, when the hosts kept returning to a graphic that ticked off 49 medal events as they happened over 48 hours (it was 51 before bad weather in Tahiti delayed the surfing). But an event doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t have to be for a medal to capture the attention of our Olympics concierges. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s been fun watching them seamlessly glide from fencing to archery to canoe slalom, sometimes learning the rules right along with viewers, without missing any of the truly crucial moments in swimming or gymnastics.  The show is also different at different times of day. Iseman and Collinsworth captain a true morning show. They appear at 7 a.m. to recap the early-morning action you may have missed, then talk about their coffee and show photos of pets watchingGold Zone. Siciliano and Hanson get more down to business during a time of day when more of the critical medal events seem to air in quick succession. The morning guys have time to fence against each other and bring in kids for a taekwondo demonstration. Hanson often feels like he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s still living inRedZone\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s witching hour.  Iseman and Collinsworth come off like longtime buddies, but they had actually never met until three days before the first show. They seem to have become best friends faster than Will Ferrell and John C. Reilly inStep Brothers.  Iseman says much of what you see on air has come together organically. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cOn Friday afternoon [before Day 1], Jac and I were talking, none of us knew what the show would be. You have an idea, but nobody\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s tried to simultaneously stream up to 40 events at a time, in dozens of different sports, and have it make sense. In our heads, we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re just picturing, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098My God, we might be stuck on speedwalking for an hour.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 Within about 15 minutes, we got it.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  They\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve remained nimble. There was a popular moment on Day 9 when a crew member came on air to break down a controversy in the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s skeet shooting final. Iseman says it was Collinsworth who suggested they put him on air, after observing an animated discussion in the studio.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThere\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s no rulebook for this,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Collinsworth says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThey made a point of telling [us] that. It makes you dip into your creative bag.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Iseman says fans have made the show better, too. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe are on Twitter reading the feedback. The quadbox got better because people were saying, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Hey that logo\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s too big.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 We agreed. We\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve jumped to the six-box, we dumped the decabox.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  They\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve also gotten more interactive as they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve found their audience.  Collinsworth says when the show first started, they were hesitant to promoteGold Zoneas its own hashtag. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Nahhh let\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s do #NBCOlympics, so we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re all on the same thing.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 But you could tell, 10 minutes into the first show, we didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t have to [ask for] #GoldZone, we were already getting hit with it.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  People who\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve come of age during this era ofRedZoneandManningCastsand putting the Super Bowl on Nickelodeon may not realize what a change this is, or what it used to be like for Olympics fans who wanted midday updates on wrestling and water polo.  Given the relative lack of interest in the Tokyo Games (thanks to a mix of COVID-19 protocols, empty stadiums and a poor time zone), I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m not sure if everyone quite remembers the extent to which criticizing NBC used to be its own Olympic sport.  I recently went back and read thisWashington Poststory from 2012about how the #NBCFail hashtag went viral. The funny thing is, at the time NBCwasstreaming everything live. I know because I actually worked for NBC during those London Games, a one-month temp position where one of my jobs was to make sure the correct livestream links for the correct judo mats were in the correct spots on the NBCOlympics.com site.  But clearly not everyone knew everything was streaming live, as made clear in that story above. Now,Gold Zonemakes life a lot easier than having to click a link that says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cRepechage, Finals: M Freestyle 55kg & 74kg.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d (And Peacock does make it easier to find those types of specific offerings.)  After Peacock hosted multiple NFL games last season, including a Miami Dolphins at Kansas City Chiefs wild-card game, people know. In 2021, NBC angered some fans by putting USA men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s basketball exclusively on Peacock andonly for paid subscribers. This time around, subscribers have gotten a lot more bang for their buck.  Whether you like it or not, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a reality of our world that streaming platforms are becoming essential for sports fans who want to watch everything. Peacock had that NFL playoff game. Netflix will have the NFL\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Christmas games. Apple TV+ has exclusive MLB windows. Amazon hasThursday Night Footballand just bought rights to the NBA.  There are still millions and millions of people who like to sit down and watch the prime-time broadcast on regular old NBC. But for those who want to see everything live\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094those taking advantage of modern work-from-home philosophies or those who simply tolerate more screen time than they did in 2016\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094Gold Zonehas been a game-changer.  As Iseman himself said, there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s no going back.  The Los Angeles Olympics in 2028 will be outstanding forGold Zoneand offer easy time slots to follow along. Brisbane, Australia, four years after that will be interesting, to see the appetite for overnightGold Zone. Some of the Winter Olympics may be interesting as well.  But now that we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve gotten a taste ofGold Zoneat its best, the people who run it must find a way to make it work. They owe it to their country.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Mitch Goldich is a senior editor for Sports Illustrated, mostly focused on the NFL. He has also covered the Olympics extensively and written on a variety of sports since joining SI in 2014. His work has been published by The New York Times, Baseball Prospectus and Food & Wine, among other outlets. Goldich has a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from Lehigh University and a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from the Medill School at Northwestern University. He is a Philly native, now living in Boston, and he invented and popularized the octopus, when the same player scores a touchdown and the ensuing two-point conversion.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"